definition.value: A disaccharide derivative that consists of  pectolinarigenin substituted by a 6-O-(6-deoxy-alpha-L-mannopyranosyl)-beta-D-glucopyranosyl moiety at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage.
A tripeptide composed of one L-glutamic acid and two L-aspartic acid units joined in sequence by peptide linkages.

A branched amino pentasaccharide comprising a trisaccahride backbone consisting of beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine and N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine residues linked in sequence (1->4) and (1->3), with alpha-L-fucose residues linked to the galactose and N-acetylglucosamine via (1->2) and (1->3) linkages respectively.

A folic acid derivative acted upon by dihydrofolate reductase to produce tetrahydrofolic acid. It interacts with bacteria during cell division and is targeted by various drugs to prevent nucleic acid synthesis.

A pyrimidine 3'-deoxyribonucleoside that is cytidine in which the hydroxy group at position 3' is replaced by a hydrogen and a double bond is introduced between positions 3' and 4'. It is a metabolite of 3'-deoxy-3',4'-didehydro-CTP.

An organic triphosphate resulting from the formal condensation of the 5'-hydroxy group of 3'-deoxy-3',4'-didehydro-cytidine with triphosphoric acid. It is a chain terminator for RNA-dependent RNA polymerases.
The 10-formyl derivative of dihydrofolic acid.

A branched amino hexasaccharide comprising a tetrasaccharide backbone consisting of alpha-D-galactose, beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine and N-acetyl-D-galactosamine residues linked in sequence (1->3), (1->4) and (1->3), with alpha-L-fucose residues linked to the beta-galactose and N-acetylglucosamine via (1->2) and (1->3) linkages respectively.
A tripeptide composed of one L-arginine and two L-aspartic acid units joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
Hexan-2-yl ester of benzoate.
Hexan-3-yl ester of benzoate.

A branched amino hexasaccharide comprising a tetrasaccharide backbone consisting of N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosamine, beta-D-galactose, N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine and N-acetyl-D-galactosamine residues linked in sequence (1->3), (1->4) and (1->3), with alpha-L-fucose residues linked to the beta-galactose and N-acetylglucosamine via (1->2) and (1->3) linkages respectively.
A derivative of folic acid in which the pteridine ring is fully reduced; it is the parent compound of a variety of coenzymes that serve as carriers of one-carbon groups in metabolic reactions.
A peptidyl nucleoside antibiotic which functions as a specific inhibitor of protein synthesis by binding ribosomal peptidyl transferase.
A diazeniumdiolate natural product found in Burkholderia cenocepacia with an antifungal activity.

A branched amino oligosaccharide comprising a beta-D-mannosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-[alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->6)]-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine branched tetrasaccharide, onto the mannosyl residue of which are two beta-D-galactosyl-(1->4)-[alpha-L-fucosyl-(1->3)]-N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl tetrasaccharide units linked (1->3) and (1->6).
A natural product found in Burkholderia cenocepacia, which zwitterion is an iron chelator with antifungal properties.
A tripeptide composed of two L-lysine units and L-leucine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A benzaldehyde that is salicylaldehyde which is substituted at position 6 by a (3S,4S,5E)-3,4-dihydroxyhepta-1,5-dien-1-yl group. It is an epimer of pyriculol with stronger phytotoxic activity.

A member of the class of 2-pyranones that is 2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogens at positions 3, 4, 5 and 6 are replaced by methyl, hydroxy, methyl and (1E,3E,5S,6R)-6-hydroxy-3,5-dimethylocta-1,3-dienyl groups, respectively. It is a polyketide isolated from the marine actinomycete Salinispora pacifica.
A tripeptide composed of L-lysine, L-leucine and L-serine joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide composed of two L-glutamic acid residues and an L-leucine residue joined in sequence by peptide linkages.
A tripeptide containing two L-glutamic acid residues and an L-lysine residue joined in sequence.
A cyclic ketone that is tropolone in which the hydrogens at positions 3 and 7 are substituted by hydroxy groups. It is isolated from the soil bacterium Streptomyces tropolofaciens strain K611-97.

A member of the class of 2-pyranones that is 2H-pyran-2-one in which the hydrogens at positions 3 and 6 are replaced by methyl and (2E)-2-buten-2-yl groups, respectively. It is a mycotoxin produced by the rice pathogen Fusarium fujikuroi.
A member of the class of benzoates that is the conjugate base of lasalocid, resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group. Major species at pH 7.3.

A member of the class of indoles that is 1-H indole with the hydrogen at position 3 substituted with a 2'-hydroxy-3'-alkoxy-4'-alkyl group. It is an antiinsectan compound found in the nematode parasite Xenorhabdus bovienii.

A form of tetrahydrofolate that acts as a donor of formyl groups in anabolism. In these reactions 10-formyltetrahydrofolic acid is used as a substrate in formyltransferase reactions, which is important in purine biosynthesis.
